17. Can String be extended (inheritance)? Why or why not?
-->String cannot be extended because it is declared as a final class, preventing inheritance for security and immutability reasons.


18. Difference between substring() and subSequence()?
-->substring() → returns String
subSequence() → returns CharSequence


19. What is StringBuffer class in Java?
-->StringBuffer is a mutable (modifiable) class used to create and manipulate strings dynamically.

    Unlike String, it does not create new objects when modified.
    It is thread-safe (synchronized).
    
    👉 Example:
    StringBuffer sb = new StringBuffer("Hello");
    sb.append(" World");
    System.out.println(sb); // Hello World



20. Is StringBuffer mutable or immutable? Is StringBuffer thread-safe? Why?
-->Mutable → Yes (can change content)
    Thread-safe → Yes
    👉 Because all its methods are synchronized, meaning only one thread can access it at a time.
    
    It achieves this because all of its public methods that modify the character sequence (such as append(), insert(), delete(), 
        and replace()) are synchronized.
        Why is StringBuffer Thread-Safe?
        Synchronized Methods: When a method is synchronized, it means that if multiple threads try to access the same StringBuffer instance, 
        only one thread can execute a method at a time.
        Object Locking: The synchronized keyword uses an implicit lock (monitor) on the StringBuffer instance. The first thread to access the
        object locks it, forcing other threads to wait until the first thread finishes its operation.



21. Difference between append() and insert() methods?
-->
| Method     | Purpose                       |
| ---------- | ----------------------------- |
| `append()` | Adds data at the end          |
| `insert()` | Adds data at a specific index |
sb.append("Java");       // end
sb.insert(0, "Hi ");     // at index 0



22. What is the default capacity of StringBuffer?
-->Default capacity = 16 characters


23. How does the capacity of StringBuffer increase dynamically?
-->Formula: newCapacity = (oldCapacity * 2) + 2

👉 Example:
Old = 16 → New = 34 → Next = 70


24. What is StringBuilder in Java?
-->StringBuilder is also a mutable string class, similar to StringBuffer, but:
    Not thread-safe
    Faster than StringBuffer




